{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d45256e5-dda2-48da-bbc6-85ca9900525e","content":"","toolRequests":[{"toolCallId":"tooluse_4WE0Cqf7HFHoeFBd7ZHoC2","name":"report_intent","arguments":{"intent":"Explaining C# 13 breaking changes"},"type":"function"},{"toolCallId":"tooluse_8pXdQsnTPRwJHIiZe5UMQV","name":"bash","arguments":{"command":"mkdir -p /tmp/sv-732b25f591aa404abfbfa7894b644eac","description":"Ensure working directory exists","initial_wait":5},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"Ensure working directory exists"}],"interactionId":"239de3db-8a8f-4c4d-9225-1901233fe14f","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about specific C# 13 / .NET 9 breaking changes. Let me analyze each case:\n\n1. **Buffer.cs** - `[InlineArray]` on a `record struct`: C# 13 disallows `[InlineArray]` on record structs. The fix is to change it to a plain `struct`.\n\n2. **Generator.cs** - `stackalloc` in a local function inside an iterator: C# 13 now allows `unsafe` code in iterators/async methods, but `stackalloc` in iterator methods is still not allowed (or rather, the rules changed). Actually, let me think more carefully. \n\nIn C# 12, `stackalloc` was allowed in local functions within iterators because the local function was treated as a separate method. But in C# 13, the compiler's handling of unsafe code in iterators changed - it now allows unsafe blocks directly in iterators, which altered how `stackalloc` is scoped. The breaking change is that `stackalloc` in a local function inside an iterator now causes an error because the compiler treats it as part of the iterator state machine rather than a separate context.\n\nActually, I need to clarify this: C# 13 introduced support for `ref struct` types in async and iterator methods, but as part of that change, `stackalloc` expressions are no longer permitted in local functions or lambdas nested within iterator or async methods. The workaround is to extract the unsafe code into a separate static method outside the iterator entirely.\n\nFor the Resolver.cs case, the issue involves collection expressions with `params Span<T>` overload resolution. In C# 13, the empty collection expression `[]` became ambiguous when choosing between `ReadOnlySpan<int>` and `Span<object>` parameters because of updated overload resolution rules around `params Span<T>`. An explicit cast resolves the ambiguity.\n\nNow I'm working through the concrete fixes for each case.","outputTokens":943},"id":"6edeb44f-833d-4296-8f16-3f5c7e95fdea","timestamp":"2026-04-08T01:10:45.964Z","parentId":"14d7ac4b-a63a-4328-8624-7bc2cd30f0ed"}
