{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"6f9b3bb6-a221-4bf3-91db-9f74510d0728","content":"Here are the three breaking changes and their fixes:\n\n---\n\n### 1. `Buffer.cs` — `[InlineArray]` on `record struct` is now an error\n\nC# 13 disallows `[InlineArray]` on record structs (they synthesize `Equals`/`GetHashCode` that don't account for all elements).\n\n**Fix:** Change `record struct` → plain `struct`:\n\n```csharp\n[System.Runtime.CompilerServices.InlineArray(10)]\nstruct Buffer\n{\n    private int _element0;\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n### 2. `Generator.cs` — `stackalloc` in local function inside an iterator\n\nC# 13 extended `ref struct` / `unsafe` support into iterators and async methods. A side effect is that `stackalloc` inside a local function of an iterator is now **disallowed** (the compiler treats it as part of the iterator state machine).\n\n**Fix:** Extract the local function to a regular `static` method:\n\n```csharp\nunsafe class DataGenerator\n{\n    IEnumerable<int> Generate()\n    {\n        yield return 1;\n        Process();\n    }\n\n    static void Process()\n    {\n        int* p = stackalloc int[10];\n        // ... work with pointer\n    }\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n### 3. `Resolver.cs` — Overload resolution ambiguity with `[]`\n\nC# 13's expanded `params` support for spans changes overload resolution. The empty collection expression `[]` now matches **both** `ReadOnlySpan<int>` and `Span<object>` equally well, making the call ambiguous.\n\n**Fix:** Add an explicit type to disambiguate:\n\n```csharp\nstatic void Main()\n{\n    Process((ReadOnlySpan<int>)[]);\n}\n```\n\nOr use `ReadOnlySpan<int>.Empty` directly.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"239de3db-8a8f-4c4d-9225-1901233fe14f","outputTokens":450},"id":"37ec4df1-0da2-4434-98a8-bd2d411c50ef","timestamp":"2026-04-08T01:10:55.235Z","parentId":"7f182a1f-265e-4025-89c4-f8c918dc316f"}
